  "prompt": "What is the full story of causality?",
  "response": "The story of causality is complex and multifaceted, spanning philosophy, science, and human understanding. Here's a comprehensive overview:\n\n1. Ancient Philosophical Origins\n- Aristotle first systematically explored causation\n- Identified four types of causes: material, formal, efficient, and final\n- Sought to understand why things happen\n\n2. Medieval Philosophical Development\n- Thomas Aquinas expanded on Aristotelian concepts\n- Introduced theological perspectives on causation\n- Explored divine causation and natural laws\n\n3. Enlightenment Scientific Revolution\n- David Hume challenged traditional causation views\n- Argued causation is based on observed regularities, not inherent necessity\n- Introduced skepticism about definitive causal links\n\n4. Scientific Emergence\n- Newton's laws established predictable cause-effect relationships\n- Classical physics assumed deterministic causal models\n- Introduced mathematical representations of causation\n\n5. Modern Scientific Understanding\n- Quantum mechanics challenged classical determinism\n- Introduced probabilistic and non-linear causation\n- Showed causality can be complex and non-linear\n\n6. Contemporary Perspectives\n- Complex systems theory\n- Networked and emergent causation\n- Probabilistic and multidimensional causal models\n\n7. Philosophical and Scientific Ongoing Debates\n- Nature of causation remains philosophically complex\n- Continuous refinement of causal understanding\n- Interdisciplinary approaches to causality\n\nEach stage represents evolving human understanding of how events interconnect and influence each other.",
